'''Nathan-Dylan Saliba''' (born February 7, 2004) is a Canadian professional [[Association football|soccer]] player who plays for [[Belgian Pro League]] club [[RSC Anderlecht|Anderlecht]] and the [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada national team]].

==Early life==
Saliba began playing youth soccer at age nine with [[CS Longueuil]].<ref name=canada/> In 2017, he joined the [[Montreal Impact Academy]].<ref name=sign /> He is of Haitian and Lebanese descent through both his parents, and can speak English, French and [[Haitian Creole]].<ref name="canada">{{Canada Soccer player|id=6550|accessdate=2026-05-04}}</ref>

==Club career==
===CF Montréal===

In December 2020, he signed his first professional contract with the [[CF Montréal|Montreal Impact]] (later re-named CF Montreal) of [[Major League Soccer]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Press |first=The Canadian |date=2020-12-04 |title=Montreal Impact promote four young midfielders from academy to first team |url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/soccer/montreal-impact-promote-four-young-midfielders-from-academy-to-first-team/article_7501db23-2d33-59d6-aa91-3cb860890b95.html |access-date=2026-05-04 |website=Toronto Star |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Canadienne |first=La Presse |date=2020-12-04 |title=Jean-Aniel Assi, Sean Rea, Nathan-Dylan Saliba et Rida Zouhir signent avec l'Impact |trans-title=Jean-Aniel Assi, Sean Rea, Nathan-Dylan Saliba and Rida Zouhir sign with the Impact |url=https://www.rds.ca/soccer/impact/jean-aniel-assi-sean-rea-nathan-dylan-saliba-et-rida-zouhir-signent-avec-l-impact-1.9079463 |access-date=2026-05-04 |website=RDS |language=fr}}</ref> He served as an unused substitute in their [[CONCACAF Champions League]] match against [[C.D. Olimpia]] on December 15, 2020.

In 2022, he played with [[CF Montréal U23]] in the [[Première ligue de soccer du Québec]], scoring four goals in seven appearances.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fieldlevelmedia.com/soccer/mls/cf-montreal-sign-homegrown-m-nathan-saliba-to-2-year-deal/|title=CF Montreal sign homegrown M Nathan Saliba to 2-year deal|date=December 2, 2022|work=Field Level Media|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref> In December 2022, he signed a two-year extension with Montreal.<ref name="sign">{{cite web|url=https://en.cfmontreal.com/news/nathan-saliba-signs-new-contract-with-cf-montreal|title=Nathan Saliba signs new contract with CF Montréal|date=December 2, 2022|work=[[CF Montréal]]|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.journaldequebec.com/2022/12/02/un-nouveau-contrat-pour-nathan-saliba-1|title=Un nouveau contrat pour Nathan Saliba|language=fr|date=December 2, 2022|trans-title=A new contract for Nathan Saliba|work=[[Le Journal de Québec]]|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref>

During the 2023 pre-season, he sought to earn a spot with the first team squad, rather than to pursue a loan to the [[Canadian Premier League]], as other Montreal young players had gone on in previous seasons<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lapresse.ca/sports/soccer/2023-01-25/camp-d-entrainement/le-cf-montreal-et-ses-elephants-dans-la-piece.php|title=Le CF Montréal et ses éléphants dans la pièce: Saliba veut tenter sa chance|trans-title=CF Montreal and its elephants in the room: Salba wants to try his luck|first=Justin|last=Vézina|date=January 25, 2023|language=fr|work=[[La Presse (Canadian newspaper)|La Presse]]|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref> and he scored a goal against the PLSQ All-Stars in a pre-season exhibition match.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rds.ca/soccer/cfm/nathan-saliba-pique-de-plus-en-plus-la-curiosite-1.16579494|title=Nathan Saliba pique la curiosité au camp du CF Montréal|trans-title=Nathan Saliba arouses curiosity at CF Montreal camp|language=fr|date=February 25, 2023|work=[[Réseau des sports|RDS]]|first=Nicolas|last=Landry|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref> He made his professional debut on February 25, 2023, starting the season opener against [[Inter Miami CF]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Landry |first=Nicolas |date=2023-02-04 |title=kooralive |url=https://kooralive.website/ |access-date=2026-05-04 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|date=February 25, 2023|first=Justin|last=Vézina|url=https://www.lapresse.ca/sports/soccer/2023-02-25/inter-miami-2-cf-montreal-0/le-cf-montreal-entame-sa-saison-avec-un-revers.php|title=Le CF Montréal entame sa saison avec un revers|trans-title=CF Montreal begins its season with a setback|language=fr|work=[[La Presse (Canadian newspaper)|La Presse]]|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref>

At the end of the 2024 season, he was named to the MLS 22 Under 22 list and was nominated for the MLS Young Player of the Year award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://canadiansoccerdaily.com/2024/10/09/canmnt-and-cf-montreal-midfielder-nathan-saliba-lone-canadian-on-mls-22-under-22-list/|title=CanMNT and CF Montréal midfielder Nathan Saliba lone Canadian on MLS 22 Under 22 list|first=Tom|last=Nightingale|date=October 9, 2024|work=Canadian Soccer Daily|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://canadiansoccerdaily.com/2024/10/30/nathan-saliba-cf-montreal-canada-dreams-of-european-move/|title=Nathan Saliba dreams of European move after hitting new heights for CF Montréal and Canada in 2024|first=Tom|last=Nightingale|date=October 30, 2024|work=Canadian Soccer Daily|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref>

===Anderlecht===
In June 2025, Saliba joined [[Belgian Pro League]] club [[R.S.C. Anderlecht|Anderlecht]] on a transfer for an undisclosed fee, signing a contract until 2029, with CF Montréal retaining a sell-on clause.<ref>{{cite web|title=Midfielder Nathan Saliba joins RSCA|website=[[RSC Anderlecht]]|date=June 26, 2025|url=https://www.rsca.be/en/news/midfielder-nathan-saliba-joins-rsca}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.cfmontreal.com/news/nathan-saliba-transferred-to-r-s-c-anderlecht|title=Nathan Saliba transferred to R.S.C. Anderlecht|date=June 26, 2025|work=[[CF Montréal]]}}</ref>

==International career==
===Youth===
In 2016, he represented Canada at the [[Danone Nations Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thesuburban.com/sports/ontario-bests-quebec-in-danone-nations-cup-canadian-championship/article_84739df0-960d-53da-b70b-b460ab005a2c.html|title=Ontario bests Quebec in Danone Nations Cup Canadian Championship|first=Mark|last=Lidbetter|work=[[The Suburban]]|date=June 29, 2016|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref><ref name=sign /> In 2019, he made his debut in the Canadian youth program at a camp with the Canada U15 team, after which he was named to the roster for the [[2019 CONCACAF Boys' Under-15 Championship]].<ref name=canada />

In 2022, he was named to the provisional roster for the [[Canada men's national under-20 soccer team|Canada U20]] team ahead of the [[2022 CONCACAF U-20 Championship]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/soccer/2022/05/18/some-familiar-names-on-canadas-provisional-roster-for-concacaf-u-20-championship.html|title=Some familiar names on Canada's provisional roster for CONCACAF U-20 Championship|date=May 18, 2022|work=[[Toronto Star]]|first=Neil|last=Davidson|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref> although he was not named to the final roster.

===Senior===
In February 2024, Saliba was named to the [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canadian senior]] provisional roster for the [[2024 Copa América qualifying play-offs]] against [[Trinidad and Tobago national football team|Trinidad and Tobago]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Concacaf Nations League Play-In preliminary rosters announced|url=https://www.concacaf.com/nations-league/news/concacaf-nations-league-play-in-preliminary-rosters-announced/|publisher=Concacaf.com |access-date=February 26, 2024 |date=February 26, 2024 |archive-date= |archive-url=|url-status=}}</ref>

In August 2024 he received a call up to Canada for friendlies against the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] and [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]], as an injury replacement for [[Samuel Adekugbe]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://canadiansoccerdaily.com/2024/09/01/cf-montreal-midfield-talent-nathan-saliba-called-up-for-canmnt-duty-by-canada-head-coach-jesse-marsch/|date=September 1, 2024|title=CF Montréal midfield talent Nathan Saliba called up for CanMNT duty by Canada head coach Jesse Marsch|work=Canadian Soccer Daily|first=Tom|last=Nightingale|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref> Saliba made his debut in the first friendly against the USA on September 7, as a late substitute in a 2-1 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://canadiansoccerdaily.com/2024/09/07/canada-blow-usmnt-out-the-water-as-shaffelburg-david-give-canmnt-emphatic-2-1-win/|date=September 7, 2024|title=Canada blow USMNT out the water as Shaffelburg, David give CanMNT emphatic 2-1 win|first=Tom|last=Nightingale|work=Canadian Soccer Daily|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref> He was named the 2024 [[Canada Soccer Young Player of the Year]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://canadasoccer.com/news/olivia-smith-and-nathan-saliba-named-canada-soccers-2024-young-players-of-the-year/|title=Olivia Smith and Nathan Saliba named Canada Soccer's 2024 Young Players of the Year|date=December 18, 2024|work=[[Canadian Soccer Association]]|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref>

In June 2025 Saliba was named to the squad for the [[2025 CONCACAF Gold Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://canadasoccer.com/news/canmnt-squad-announced-for-2025-concacaf-gold-cup/#:~:text=Defenders%20selected%20are%3A%20Sam%20Adekugbe,Niko%20Sigur%20from%20Hadjuk%20Split%2C|date=June 5, 2025|title=CANMNT squad announced for 2025 Concacaf Gold Cup|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref> On June 17 in Canada's opening game against [[Honduras national football team|Honduras]], he would score his first international goal in a 6-0 victory at [[BC Place]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/news/tani-time-oluwaseyi-leads-canada-past-honduras-in-gold-cup-opener|title=Tani time! Oluwaseyi leads Canada past Honduras in Gold Cup opener|date=June 18, 2025|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref>

